puniendam] We may guess what ‘ a ju- dicibus puniendam’ means, but nobody will suppose that the Romans said ‘domus a judicibus punienda est;' nor ‘munienda’ either, as Baiter has it, adopting a correc- tion. Ernesti thinks that ‘puniendam ’ is to be taken in the sense of ‘ulciscendam' “Punire domum est poenam repetere ob violatam domum” (Ernesti, Index Latin). He refers to the De Oratore i. 51 : ‘⁴ eupi- ditas puniendi doloris ;’' Pro Milone i. 13: “tu me tibi iratum, Sexte, putas, cnjus inimicissimum multo crudelius etiam poe- nitus es quam erat humanitatis meae pos- tulare ?” and Phil. viii. 2. These passages show the meaning of ‘ punire‚’ but they do not justify the expression in the text.

linqua . . . manu . . . manibus] Here we have the Declamator’s hand. So 31 1116 end of the De Domo, c. 58: “auctoritate studio, sententiis re- stituistis . . . manibus quoque vestris in 56- dibus meis collocetis.'’ So we shall learn to write at last by studying this author.
